04877nam a22007815i 9780824863166DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20002000hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029830372  a(OCoLC)1032695367  a(OCoLC)1037982827  a(OCoLC)1041989247  a(OCoLC)1046616101  a(OCoLC)1047015235  a(OCoLC)1049632852  a(OCoLC)1054881631  a97808248631667 a10.1515/97808248631662doi  a(DE-B1597)484284  a(OCoLC)1024056458  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0210002bisacsh0483pa320qDE-1011 aBrooks, Barbara J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJapan's Imperial Diplomacy :bConsuls, Treaty Ports, and War in China, 1895-1938 /cBarbara J. Brooks. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Rise of Kasumigaseki Diplomacy The Struggle for Autonomy -- t2. The Development of the Career Diplomat Nurturing China Expertise -- t3 .The Japanese Consul in China -- t4. The Gaimushò’s Loss in the Manchurian Incident -- t5 .The Path to War The Gaimushò’s Continuing Loss of Control in China Affairs -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn November 1937, Ishii Itaro, head of the Japanese Foreign Ministry's Bureau of Asiatic Affairs, reflected bitterly on the decline of the ministry's influence in China and his own long and debilitating struggle to guide China policy. Ishii was the most notable member of a group of middle-level diplomats who, having served in China, strongly advocated that Japan adopt policies in harmony with China's rising nationalism and national interests. Japan's Imperial Diplomacy profiles this distinct strain of "China service diplomat," while providing a comprehensive look at the institutional history and internal dynamics of the Japanese Foreign Ministry and its handling of China affairs in the years leading up to and through World War II.Moving from a thorough examination of a wide range of primary sources, including the extensive archives of the Japanese Foreign Ministry, memoirs, diaries, and unpublished speeches, Japan's Imperial Diplomacy offers integrated interpretations of Japanese imperialism, diplomacy, and the bureaucratic restructuring of the 1930s that were fundamental to Japan's version of fascism and the move toward war. Specialists of China, Japan, comparative colonialism, and World War II diplomacy will find this well-conceived and carefully researched and organized work of first-rate importance to the understanding of modern Japanese history in general and Japanese imperialism in particular.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486316640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824863166423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824863166.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL